Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

E-news Express fundamentally aims to expand its business. To achieve this, they want to review their online (website) platform's performance and leverage it to acquire new subscribers. Consequently, we queried data on 100 randomly selected users and divided them into two equal groups. One group represented a control group, to query user behavior on the existing platform and the other a treatment group, to query data on a new platform. The collected data was processed and analyzed to extract reliable insights and propose effective recommendations. Our analysis followed these guidelines:

  • Examine the time spent on the new landing page and the existing landing page.
  • Study the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page and the conversion rate for the old page.
  • Verify the relationship between the converted status and the preferred language.
  • Explore the time spent on the new page the same for different language users.

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

The mean time spent by users on the new landing page is 4.53
The mean time spent by users on the new landing page is 6.22
In [61]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,7)); #display the graph with the given size specifiations for the x-axis and y-axis respectively.
sns.boxplot(data = df, x = 'landing_page', y = 'time_spent_on_the_page' ); #Create a boxplot for the values in this column.
plt.xlabel('Time Spent on Old Page Vs Time Spent On New Page'); #display title in bracket as x-axis label

Observation:

  • Users on the new landing page spent more time on the page than users on the old page.
  • The minimum amount of time spent by a user on the new page is significantly greater than that of the old group hinting more preference or activity on the new landing page.
  • Both groups do not show any significant skewness in their distributions.
  • There are outlier values in the distribution for the new page but an absence in its counterpart's.

We will test this analysis further to learn more.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let 𝜇1, 𝜇2 be the mean times spent on the new page and the old page respectively.

Null Hypothesis can be written as $H_0$ : 𝜇1 = 𝜇2

Alternate Hypothesis can be written as $H_a$ : 𝜇1 > 𝜇2

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

  • This is a one-tailed test concerning two population means from two independent populations.
  • Continuous data - The usage time is measured on a continuous scale.
  • Normally distributed populations or Sample sizes > 30 - Since the sample sizes are greater than 30, Central Limit Theorem states that the distribution of sample means will be normal.
  • The population standard deviations are unknown or unstated.
  • As the sample standard deviations are different, the population standard deviations may be assumed to be different.
  • Random sampling from the population - The project description states that the collected sample was randomly collected.

The above assumptions make the Two Independent Sample T-Test for equality of means viable for this problem. The test statistic distribution will be the t-distribution.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the project description, we select $\alpha = 0.05$.

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

#compare standard deviations of the two groups to set equal_var parameter in p-value function
std_old = df_old['time_spent_on_the_page'].std()

if std_old == std_new :
    print('The standard deviations of the two groups are equal!')
elif std_old != std_new :
    print('The standard deviations of the two groups are not equal!')

The standard deviations of the two groups are not equal!

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

Based on our assumptions we will use ttest_ind function to compute the p-value.¶

As the two standard deviations are not equal, we set equal_var parameter to False.¶

The alternative hypothesis is a right tailed test so we set alternative parameter to greater.¶

In [65]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind #required function for computation

#Computing p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'], df_old['time_spent_on_the_page'], equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater' )

print('The p-value is', p_value) #print p-value in a statement.

The p-value is 0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [66]:
# compare both values and print appropriate statement.
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001392381225166549 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

As the p-value (~0.0001) is less than the value of $\alpha$ (0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis.
This follows the principle that if null is low, null must go.
Hence, we have enough statistical evidence to show that the users spend more time on the new page than on the old one.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

Visual Analysis¶

Observation:

  • There were more subscribers in the new page compared to the old page.
  • Conversely, the number of users that did not subscribe on the old page is greater than the new page's.

We will test this analysis further to learn more.

Step 1 : Define the null and alternate hypothesis for the problem¶

Let p1, p2 be the proportions for the conversion rate of the new page and the old page respectively.

Null Hypothesis $H_0$ : p1 = p2

Alternate Hypothesis $H_a$ : p1 > p2

Step 2 : Select appropriate test¶

  • Binomally distributed population - Auser either subscribed or did not subscribe.
  • Random sampling from the population - The details from the experiment state that the users were randomly selected.
  • The populations are independent of each other.
  • To approximate normal distribution we check if both np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10 where n is the sample size and p is the sample proportion respectively. This computation will make the two proportions z-test suitable for this analysis.

Approximating normal distribution¶

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Null Hypothesis: $H_0:$ The converted status is independent of the preferred language.

Alternative Hypothesis: $H_a:$ The converted status depends on the preferred language.

Step 2: Selecting appropriate test¶

The above problem fits the Chi-square test of independence as it meets the following requirements:

  • Two categorical variables - converted and language preferred.
  • The expected value of the number of sample observations in each level of the observations is more than 5.
  • The samples were randomly selected from the population.

Step 3: Define Significance level¶

As given in the project descriptiont, we select α = 0.05.

4. Is the time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

Visual Analysis¶

In [81]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12,7));  #display the graph with the given size specifiations for the x-axis and y-axis respectively.

plt.title('Comparing time spent on the new page per the different languages'); #insert title for bar graph

Observation:

  • The mean times spent on the new page by the different language users vary significantly.
  • English users had the greatest average time spent on the new page while the French users had the least.
  • The English and French users'distribution are left skewed while the French users'distribution shows a right skewed distribution.

We will test this analysis further to learn more.

Step 1: Define the null and alternative hypotheses¶

Let Let $\mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3$ be the average time spent on the new page for English, Spanish and French respectively.

Null hypothesis: The mean time spent on the new page for all three language users are the equal.

$H_0:$ $\mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3$

Alternative hypothesis: $H_a: $ At least one of the mean times spent on the new page is different from the other preferred languages.

Step 2: Select appropriate test¶

The normality and equality of variances assumptions need to be checked.
We will verify this with the Shapiro-Wilk's test and the Levene's test using the shapiro() function and levene() function respectively to compute the test statistic and p-value.

1. Shapiro-Wilk's Test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ Time soent on new page follows a normal distribution against

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a:$ Time spent on new page does not follow a normal distribution

In [82]:
#Normality test
# import the required function
from scipy import stats

# compute the p-value
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(df_new['time_spent_on_the_page']) 

print('The p-value is', p_value) 

if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

The p-value is 0.8040016293525696
As the p-value 0.8040016293525696 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

2. Levene's Test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0$: All the population variances are equal

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a$: At least one variance is different from the rest

In [83]:
#Homogeneity of Variance test
#import the required function
from scipy.stats import levene
statistic, p_value = levene( df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred'] == "English"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred'] == "Spanish"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred'] == "French"])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.46711357711340173 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

The computations satisfy the following asumptions:

  • The populations are normally distributed as verified by the Shapiro-Wilk’s test.
  • Samples are independent simple random samples as stated in the problem statement.
  • Population variances are equal as verified by the Levene's test.

Step 3: Define significance level.¶

We consider the significance level to be 0.05 as stated in the problem statement.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

Conclusions:¶

  • 100 users were randomly selected and divided into two equal groups to undertake this experiment.
  • Generally, users spent more time on the new page than the old one possibly affirming any changes or enhancements that were made to the old one may have been successful.
  • Also, there were more subscriptions on the new page than the old one hinting a general preference for the new page.
  • The subscriptions that were made were independent of the language of the users. Other metrics can be focused and improved. - The most amount of time spent on the page is at most 11 minutes while the least amount of time spent on the page is 11.4 seconds. 11.4 seconds is a small amount of time to spend on a website. This is possibly due to a technical error but this could be investigated further to uncover more details.
  • Generally, users spent about 5.4 minutes on the page regardless of the category (control or treatment group).
  • Three unique languages were considered for this experiment- Spanish, English and French.
  • Spanish recorded the least amount of time spent on the page by a user whilst the french recorded the highest amount of time spent by a user.
  • The maximum time recorded by a user on the control page was in the English group while the least amount of time spent on the page by a user was in the spanish group.
  • The french group preferred the new page more than the old one. This is perhaps due to favorable additions that were made to the old one.

Recommendations:¶

  • Other languages could be installed on the online platform to create a more diverse platform and consequently attract people who speak other languages.
  • The french group showed a high preference for the new page. Further query could be done to understand these preferences and possibly implement some of these ideas on the English and Spanish pages.
  • The website should be scraped of external advertisements, if any, that may distract users and reduce the activity or the time spent on the page.
  • The use of video or audio files could be used on the website to allow users assimilate more information quicker as reading could be relatively tedious and possibly deter users from spending time on the website.
  • Further analysis could be done to investigate the influence of subscription charges, if any, on users as it could also influence conversion rate.
  • A comment section could be included on the platform to allow users share reviews and help to streamline any future improvements that may need to be done.
